\title{Markitdown}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Convert files and office documents to Markdown. Supports PDF, DOCX, PPTX, XLSX, images (with OCR), audio (with transcription), HTML, CSV, JSON, XML, ZIP, YouTube URLs, EPubs and more."}

\subtree{
\title{MarkItDown - File to Markdown Conversion}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{MarkItDown is a Python tool developed by Microsoft for converting various file formats to Markdown. It's particularly useful for converting documents into LLM-friendly text format, as Markdown is token-efficient and well-understood by modern language models.}

\p{\strong{Key Benefits}:}

\ul{
\li{Convert documents to clean, structured Markdown}
\li{Token-efficient format for LLM processing}
\li{Supports 15+ file formats}
\li{Optional AI-enhanced image descriptions}
\li{OCR for images and scanned documents}
\li{Speech transcription for audio files}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Visual Enhancement with Scientific Schematics}
\p{\strong{When creating documents with this skill, always consider adding scientific diagrams and schematics to enhance visual communication.}}

\p{If your document does not already contain schematics or diagrams:}

\ul{
\li{Use the \strong{scientific-schematics} skill to generate AI-powered publication-quality diagrams}
\li{Simply describe your desired diagram in natural language}
\li{Nano Banana Pro will automatically generate, review, and refine the schematic}
}

\p{\strong{For new documents:} Scientific schematics should be generated by default to visually represent key concepts, workflows, architectures, or relationships described in the text.}

\p{\strong{How to generate schematics:}}

\pre{\startverb
python scripts/generate_schematic.py "your diagram description" -o figures/output.png
\stopverb}

\p{The AI will automatically:}

\ul{
\li{Create publication-quality images with proper formatting}
\li{Review and refine through multiple iterations}
\li{Ensure accessibility (colorblind-friendly, high contrast)}
\li{Save outputs in the figures/ directory}
}

\p{\strong{When to add schematics:}}

\ul{
\li{Document conversion workflow diagrams}
\li{File format architecture illustrations}
\li{OCR processing pipeline diagrams}
\li{Integration workflow visualizations}
\li{System architecture diagrams}
\li{Data flow diagrams}
\li{Any complex concept that benefits from visualization}
}

\p{For detailed guidance on creating schematics, refer to the scientific-schematics skill documentation.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Supported Formats}
\pre{\startverb
| Format | Description | Notes |
|--------|-------------|-------|
| **PDF** | Portable Document Format | Full text extraction |
| **DOCX** | Microsoft Word | Tables, formatting preserved |
| **PPTX** | PowerPoint | Slides with notes |
| **XLSX** | Excel spreadsheets | Tables and data |
| **Images** | JPEG, PNG, GIF, WebP | EXIF metadata + OCR |
| **Audio** | WAV, MP3 | Metadata + transcription |
| **HTML** | Web pages | Clean conversion |
| **CSV** | Comma-separated values | Table format |
| **JSON** | JSON data | Structured representation |
| **XML** | XML documents | Structured format |
| **ZIP** | Archive files | Iterates contents |
| **EPUB** | E-books | Full text extraction |
| **YouTube** | Video URLs | Fetch transcriptions |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\pre{\startverb
# Install with all features
pip install 'markitdown[all]'

# Or from source
git clone https://github.com/microsoft/markitdown.git
cd markitdown
pip install -e 'packages/markitdown[all]'
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Command-Line Usage}
\pre{\startverb
# Basic conversion
markitdown document.pdf > output.md

# Specify output file
markitdown document.pdf -o output.md

# Pipe content
cat document.pdf | markitdown > output.md

# Enable plugins
markitdown --list-plugins  # List available plugins
markitdown --use-plugins document.pdf -o output.md
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Python API}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown

# Basic usage
md = MarkItDown()
result = md.convert("document.pdf")
print(result.text_content)

# Convert from stream
with open("document.pdf", "rb") as f:
    result = md.convert_stream(f, file_extension=".pdf")
    print(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advanced Features}
\subtree{
\title{1. AI-Enhanced Image Descriptions}
\p{Use LLMs via OpenRouter to generate detailed image descriptions (for PPTX and image files):}

\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown
from openai import OpenAI

# Initialize OpenRouter client (OpenAI-compatible API)
client = OpenAI(
    api_key="your-openrouter-api-key",
    base_url="https://openrouter.ai/api/v1"
)

md = MarkItDown(
    llm_client=client,
    llm_model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.5",  # recommended for scientific vision
    llm_prompt="Describe this image in detail for scientific documentation"
)

result = md.convert("presentation.pptx")
print(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Azure Document Intelligence}
\p{For enhanced PDF conversion with Microsoft Document Intelligence:}

\pre{\startverb
# Command line
markitdown document.pdf -o output.md -d -e "<document_intelligence_endpoint>"
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
# Python API
from markitdown import MarkItDown

md = MarkItDown(docintel_endpoint="<document_intelligence_endpoint>")
result = md.convert("complex_document.pdf")
print(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Plugin System}
\p{MarkItDown supports 3rd-party plugins for extending functionality:}

\pre{\startverb
# List installed plugins
markitdown --list-plugins

# Enable plugins
markitdown --use-plugins file.pdf -o output.md
\stopverb}

\p{Find plugins on GitHub with hashtag: \code{\startverb #markitdown-plugin\stopverb}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Optional Dependencies}
\p{Control which file formats you support:}

\pre{\startverb
# Install specific formats
pip install 'markitdown[pdf, docx, pptx]'

# All available options:
# [all]                  - All optional dependencies
# [pptx]                 - PowerPoint files
# [docx]                 - Word documents
# [xlsx]                 - Excel spreadsheets
# [xls]                  - Older Excel files
# [pdf]                  - PDF documents
# [outlook]              - Outlook messages
# [az-doc-intel]         - Azure Document Intelligence
# [audio-transcription]  - WAV and MP3 transcription
# [youtube-transcription] - YouTube video transcription
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Use Cases}
\subtree{
\title{1. Convert Scientific Papers to Markdown}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown

md = MarkItDown()

# Convert PDF paper
result = md.convert("research_paper.pdf")
with open("paper.md", "w") as f:
    f.write(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Extract Data from Excel for Analysis}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown

md = MarkItDown()
result = md.convert("data.xlsx")

# Result will be in Markdown table format
print(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Process Multiple Documents}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown
import os
from pathlib import Path

md = MarkItDown()

# Process all PDFs in a directory
pdf_dir = Path("papers/")
output_dir = Path("markdown_output/")
output_dir.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

for pdf_file in pdf_dir.glob("*.pdf"):
    result = md.convert(str(pdf_file))
    output_file = output_dir / f"{pdf_file.stem}.md"
    output_file.write_text(result.text_content)
    print(f"Converted: {pdf_file.name}")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Convert PowerPoint with AI Descriptions}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown
from openai import OpenAI

# Use OpenRouter for access to multiple AI models
client = OpenAI(
    api_key="your-openrouter-api-key",
    base_url="https://openrouter.ai/api/v1"
)

md = MarkItDown(
    llm_client=client,
    llm_model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.5",  # recommended for presentations
    llm_prompt="Describe this slide image in detail, focusing on key visual elements and data"
)

result = md.convert("presentation.pptx")
with open("presentation.md", "w") as f:
    f.write(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. Batch Convert with Different Formats}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown
from pathlib import Path

md = MarkItDown()

# Files to convert
files = [
    "document.pdf",
    "spreadsheet.xlsx",
    "presentation.pptx",
    "notes.docx"
]

for file in files:
    try:
        result = md.convert(file)
        output = Path(file).stem + ".md"
        with open(output, "w") as f:
            f.write(result.text_content)
        print(f"✓ Converted {file}")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"✗ Error converting {file}: {e}")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. Extract YouTube Video Transcription}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown

md = MarkItDown()

# Convert YouTube video to transcript
result = md.convert("https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VIDEO_ID")
print(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Docker Usage}
\pre{\startverb
# Build image
docker build -t markitdown:latest .

# Run conversion
docker run --rm -i markitdown:latest < ~/document.pdf > output.md
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\subtree{
\title{1. Choose the Right Conversion Method}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Simple documents}: Use basic \code{\startverb MarkItDown()\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Complex PDFs}: Use Azure Document Intelligence}
\li{\strong{Visual content}: Enable AI image descriptions}
\li{\strong{Scanned documents}: Ensure OCR dependencies are installed}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Handle Errors Gracefully}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown

md = MarkItDown()

try:
    result = md.convert("document.pdf")
    print(result.text_content)
except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File not found")
except Exception as e:
    print(f"Conversion error: {e}")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Process Large Files Efficiently}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown

md = MarkItDown()

# For large files, use streaming
with open("large_file.pdf", "rb") as f:
    result = md.convert_stream(f, file_extension=".pdf")
    
    # Process in chunks or save directly
    with open("output.md", "w") as out:
        out.write(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Optimize for Token Efficiency}
\p{Markdown output is already token-efficient, but you can:}

\ul{
\li{Remove excessive whitespace}
\li{Consolidate similar sections}
\li{Strip metadata if not needed}
}

\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown
import re

md = MarkItDown()
result = md.convert("document.pdf")

# Clean up extra whitespace
clean_text = re.sub(r'\n{3,}', '\n\n', result.text_content)
clean_text = clean_text.strip()

print(clean_text)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Integration with Scientific Workflows}
\subtree{
\title{Convert Literature for Review}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown
from pathlib import Path

md = MarkItDown()

# Convert all papers in literature folder
papers_dir = Path("literature/pdfs")
output_dir = Path("literature/markdown")
output_dir.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

for paper in papers_dir.glob("*.pdf"):
    result = md.convert(str(paper))
    
    # Save with metadata
    output_file = output_dir / f"{paper.stem}.md"
    content = f"# {paper.stem}\n\n"
    content += f"**Source**: {paper.name}\n\n"
    content += "---\n\n"
    content += result.text_content
    
    output_file.write_text(content)

# For AI-enhanced conversion with figures
from openai import OpenAI

client = OpenAI(
    api_key="your-openrouter-api-key",
    base_url="https://openrouter.ai/api/v1"
)

md_ai = MarkItDown(
    llm_client=client,
    llm_model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.5",
    llm_prompt="Describe scientific figures with technical precision"
)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Extract Tables for Analysis}
\pre{\startverb
from markitdown import MarkItDown
import re

md = MarkItDown()
result = md.convert("data_tables.xlsx")

# Markdown tables can be parsed or used directly
print(result.text_content)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\subtree{
\title{Common Issues}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Missing dependencies}: Install feature-specific packages}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Binary file errors}: Ensure files are opened in binary mode}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{OCR not working}: Install tesseract}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Performance Considerations}
\ul{
\li{\strong{PDF files}: Large PDFs may take time; consider page ranges if supported}
\li{\strong{Image OCR}: OCR processing is CPU-intensive}
\li{\strong{Audio transcription}: Requires additional compute resources}
\li{\strong{AI image descriptions}: Requires API calls (costs may apply)}
}
}

